        <body>
            <div type="leaf">
                <p>
                    <pb facs="#f024"/>
                </p>
                <p>Young Goodman<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi> too<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi> in allegorical pursuit of his Puritan wife<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi> you cry out in your anguish<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,--</hi>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">
                        <corr xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"
                            change="#StE"
                            facs="#f024_z067"
                            rend="#comp">"</corr>
                    </hi>
                    <corr change="#StE" facs="#f024_z067" rend="#comp">'</corr>Faith<corr change="#StE" facs="#f024_z024" rend="#comp">!</corr>
                    <hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">
                        <corr xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"
                            change="#StE"
                            facs="#f024_z024"
                            rend="#comp">'</corr>
                    </hi> shouted Goodman Brown, in a voice of agony<lb/> and desperation; and the echoes of the forest mocked him, crying--<lb/>
                    <hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">
                        <corr xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"
                            change="#StE"
                            facs="#f024_z023"
                            rend="#comp">'</corr>
                    </hi>Faith! Faith!<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">
                        <corr xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"
                            change="#StE"
                            facs="#f024_z022"
                            rend="#comp">'</corr>
                    </hi> as if bewildered wretches were seeking her all through<lb/> the wilderness."<lb/>
                </p>
                <p>Now this same piece<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi> entitled "<corr change="#StB" facs="#f024_z020" rend="no-caret">Y</corr>oung Goodman Brown<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">
                    <corr xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"
                        change="#StE"
                        facs="#f024_z065"
                        rend="#comp">,</corr>
                </hi>
                    <corr change="#StE" facs="#f024_z065" rend="#comp">"</corr>
                    <lb/> is one of the two that I had not all read yesterday<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">;</hi>
                    <lb/> and I allude to it now<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi> because it is<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">, </hi>in itself<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi> such a<lb/> strong positive illustration of that blackness in Hawthorne<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi>
                    <lb/> which I had assumed from the mere<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">occasional </hi>shadows of it<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi>
                    <lb/> as revealed in several of the other sketches<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">.</hi> But had I<lb/> previously perused "Young Goodman Brown<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">
                        <corr xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"
                            change="#StE"
                            facs="#f024_z057"
                            rend="#comp">,</corr>
                    </hi>
                    <corr change="#StE" facs="#f024_z057" rend="#comp">"</corr> I should have been<lb/> at no pains to draw the conclusion<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi> which I came to<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">, </hi>at<lb/> a time<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi> when I was ignorant that the book contained<lb/> one such direct and unqualified manifestation of it.<lb/>
                </p>
                <p>The other piece of the two referred to<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi> is entitled "A<lb/> Select Party<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">
                    <corr xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"
                        change="#StE"
                        facs="#f024_z052"
                        rend="#comp">,</corr>
                </hi>
                    <corr change="#StE" facs="#f024_z052" rend="#comp">" </corr>which<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi> in my first simplicity upon <reg facs="#f024_z015 #f024_z016">originally </reg>
                    <orig facs="#f024_z015 #f024_z016">origin-<lb/>ally </orig>taking hold of the book<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi> I fancied must treat of some<lb/> pumpkin-pie party in Old Salem<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi> or some <hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">chowder party</hi> on<lb/> Cape Cod<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">.</hi> Whereas<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi> by all the gods of <hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold"/>
                    <hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">Peedee!</hi> it is the<lb/> sweetest and sublimest thing that has been written<lb/> since Spencer wrote<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">.</hi> Nay, there is nothing in Spencer that<lb/>
                    <hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">surpasses</hi> it<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi>
                    <hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">perhaps, nothing that equals it. </hi>And the test is this<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">:</hi> read any canto in<lb/> "The Faery Queen<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">
                        <corr xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"
                            change="#StE"
                            facs="#f024_z042"
                            rend="#comp">,</corr>
                    </hi>
                    <corr change="#StE" facs="#f024_z042" rend="#comp">"</corr> and then read "A Select Party<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">
                        <corr xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"
                            change="#StE"
                            facs="#f024_z041"
                            rend="#comp">,</corr>
                    </hi>
                    <corr change="#StE" facs="#f024_z041" rend="#comp">"</corr> and decide<lb/> which pleases you the most<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,--</hi>
                    <hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">that is, if you are qualified to judge. </hi>Do not be frightened<lb/> at this<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">;</hi> for when Spencer was alive<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi> he was thought of<lb/> very much as Hawthorne is now<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">, --</hi> was generally<lb/>
                    <hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">accounted </hi>just such a "gentle" harmless man<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">.</hi> It may be<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi>
                    <lb/> that to common eyes<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi> the sublimity of Hawthorne seems<lb/> lost in his sweetness<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">, --</hi> as perhaps in this same "Select Party"<lb/> of his<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">;</hi> for whom<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi> he has builded so august a dome of<lb/>sunset clouds<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi> and served them on richer plate<hi xmlns="" xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" rend="bold">,</hi> than</p>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
</TEI>
